{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413012"},"attributes":{"position":3,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:51:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:51:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261097"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261097"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489669"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261097"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:50:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":7,"questionsAnswered":6,"marksTotal":6,"marksAttainable":6,"marksAttempted":6,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:51:34+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.17,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.07,0.16,0.48,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67354"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/715"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52806"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1258"},{"type":"tags","id":"1266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1267"},{"type":"tags","id":"3459"},{"type":"tags","id":"3893"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43807"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67354"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 49-year-old woman presents to the emergency department in a regional hospital with a three day history of vomiting. Over the last two weeks she has developed anorexia and early satiety. Two months ago she was discharged from hospital after an episode of severe gallstone-related acute pancreatitis. She is dehydrated with a blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg and pulse rate of 90/min. There is a fullness in the epigastrium but no succussion splash.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","Endoscopic ultrasound","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","CT abdomen","Gastroscopy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is logical to consider a connection between the recent illness and the current problem. The recent episode of pancreatitis could have been complicated by pseudocyst formation. About 10% of these patients will develop a pseudocyst, although in most cases the pseudocyst will not be of any clinical significance and will resolve spontaneously. In a small percentage of cases the pseudocyst will continue to increase in size and become troublesome - it is quite possible that this is the current problem with this patient. A \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate investigation and will help define the problem. A thick walled, rounded, fluid-filled mass adjacent to the pancreas is indicative of pancreatic pseudocyst. CT scan has a sensitivity of 90-100% in the detection of pseudocysts. Here is an example (Image). There is a large, well circumscribed cystic lesion in the region of the head of the pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn\u003Cstrong\u003E ERCP \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be a diagnostic process for a suspected pancreatic pseudocyst, but an endoscopic assessment could be used if some form of drainage procedure was considered. \u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Eis usually used secondary to other imaging techniques such as CT/MRI to further evaluate the nature of the cyst. It can be used to differentiate between a pseudocyst and or other cystic lesions of the pancreas such as neoplasm. In the case of a pseudocyst, endoscopic ultrasound can be used to judge the proximity of the cyst to the stomach to facilitate drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn\u003Cstrong\u003E MRCP \u003C/strong\u003Eis usually a better diagnostic tool than CT for evaluating pancreatic pseudocyst as MCRP/MRI provides a higher contrast resolution and is also more sensitive in detecting static fluids in the T2 weighted image. However, cost and availability of MRCP/MRI could be an issue in a regional centre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroscopy \u003C/strong\u003Eis not a usual choice of diagnosing pancreatic pseudocyst. It could be used as a method of facilitating endoscopic drainage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic pseudocyst is a common complication of acute pancreatitis."],"references":["Habashi S, Draganov PV. Pancreatic pseudocyst. World journal of gastroenterology: WJG. 2009;15(1):38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19115466/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52806"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20931"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20931"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/YOyhwcQozRI88Ist3NXwxJtZgDPfjX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/YOyhwcQozRI88Ist3NXwxJtZgDPfjX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":440,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52806"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T23:36:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T23:36:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"715"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67354"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji